== The Role of Social Sorting in Intensifying Affective Polarization
Lilliana Mason developed the concept of "social sorting" to explain how the growing alignment of partisan and ideological identities intensifies affective polarization independently of positions on issues.@mason2015disrespectfully
Social sorting refers to "the process by which an individual's multiple social identities (partisan, ideological, racial, religious) progressively align along a single dimension"@mason2015disrespectfully@mason2016partisan
When an American citizen is simultaneously a Democrat, liberal, urban, non-religious, and a member of an ethnic minority, all these identities mutually reinforce each other and create a "stacked" political identity.
Mason demonstrates empirically that "individuals whose level of partisan-ideological sorting increased over time became much angrier, without necessarily becoming more extreme in their political positions"@mason2015disrespectfully
In her analysis of the ANES 1992-1996 panel, she shows that when an individual goes through a process of aligning their partisan and ideological identities, they emerge angrier than when they entered, but not more extreme on policy issues. This result suggests that "the directional contribution of sorting precedes anger in a way that issue polarization does not"@mason2015disrespectfully

