== The Ideological Foundations Thesis of Affective Polarization
In direct opposition to the social identity perspective, Webster and Abramowitz (2017) argue that ideological polarization has been a major contributor to affective polarization.@webster2017ideological
"ideological polarization – that is, the secular process by which Democrats and Republicans in the electorate have consistently moved toward the ideological left and right respectively on a set of policy preferences – has been a major contributor to affective polarization"@webster2017ideological 
>> http://www.stevenwwebster.com/affective.pdf

Their analysis shows that the policy preferences of Democratic and Republican elites and voters have considerably diverged on a wide range of issues over recent decades, especially on questions concerning the size and role of government.
When partisans are exposed to information indicating that an opposing party candidate is an "extreme ideologue," their affective evaluations of that candidate decrease significantly. Conversely, when exposed to an opposing party candidate described as a "moderate ideologue," their positive feelings increase.@webster2017ideological

Rogowski and Sutherland (2016) reinforce this perspective by showing that "citizens respond to ideological divergence with increased affective polarization" 
Their experimental study on a nationally representative sample reveals that increasing ideological differences between political figures produces increasingly polarized affective evaluations, and that these differences are particularly pronounced among respondents with stronger ideological commitments and higher levels of political interest
@rogowski2016ideology

