==  Ideological Identity Versus Issue-Based Ideology
An important contribution to this debate comes from the analytical distinction between ideological identity (attachment to the "liberal" or "conservative" label) and issue-based ideology (actual positions on policies).

Druckman and Levendusky (2019) pose the crucial question: "What do we measure when we measure affective polarization?". They emphasize that affective polarization may have different roots and that policy preferences on issues play an important role in forming partisan feelings, even if social identity processes are also at work.@druckman2019we
- This perspective recognizes that affective polarization is not a monolithic phenomenon and that different dimensions of ideology – identity versus issues – may contribute differently to partisan animosity.

== Issue Alignment and Ideological Constraint
An important development in this debate concerns the evolution of issue alignment (ie : issue that relate to each others, for exampel : If a respondent is against gun control, issue alignment implies one can more accurately guess they also prefer lower inheritance taxes and stricter immigration policy because these stances load on the same ideological dimension.) in the American public.

 Baldassarri and Gelman (2008) documented that Americans were "partisans without constraint" – that is, they were becoming more partisan without their beliefs on a wide range of issues becoming more ideologically structured. Their analysis covering 1972-2004 showed that the relationship between people's attitudes and their partisan affiliation had tightened, but there was little evidence of issue alignment.@baldassarri2008partisans
 >> https://sites.stat.columbia.edu/gelman/research/published/B&G_PartisansWithoutConstraint_final.pdf
 
However, Kozlowski and Murphy (2021) challenged this conclusion with more recent data covering 1972-2016. They observe that "partisan alignment continued to intensify at an accelerated pace from the 2000s onward, and most notably, there was a significant increase in issue alignment in recent years" @kozlowski2021issue
They find particularly notable increases in correlations between economic and civil rights issues, while moral issues showed more modest increases. This finding challenges academic and public narratives that emphasize morally charged "culture wars" in contemporary politics, suggesting instead that race and class issues are central sources of political division.@kozlowski2021issue

The emergence of issue alignment indicates that Baldassarri and Gelman's representation of the American public as "partisans without constraint" is less accurate today than it was in 2004. These results suggest that the public is not only becoming more partisan, but that its beliefs on a wide range of issues are becoming ideologically structured. These trends challenge Philip Converse's long-standing claim that the public is "innocent of ideology"

== Comparative perspectives : European multiparty systems : 

The extension of research on affective polarization to European multiparty is a good way to nuances the debate about affective polarization  and its link to ideological polarization.

Wagner (2021, 2024) demonstrates that "in European multiparty systems, perceived ideological distance is a strong predictor of affective polarization" (ie ==> . The more citizens perceive a party as ideologically distant from them on the left-right axis, the more likely they are to experience animosity toward supporters of that party) @wagner2021affective @wagner2024affective.
However, Wagner also notes that "the strong correlation between ideological polarization and affective polarization poses a conceptual problem: if the two are highly correlated, what does the study of affective polarization add to what we already know from studying ideological polarization?". This question is particularly relevant in European contexts where affective polarization appears to be more directly linked to policy disagreements than in the United States.@wagner2024affective

Reiljan (2020, 2025) showed that affective polarization exists in European multiparty systems but varies considerably across national contexts. "Southern Europe and Central and Eastern Europe display the highest scores, followed by North America and Oceania, while Western Europe, Latin America, and Asia present somewhat lower levels"@reiljan2020fear
 This variation suggests that contextual factors – political institutions, party systems, social cleavages – play an important role in shaping affective polarization.

 Comellas  (2023) made an important contribution by examining the role of ideological identity relative to issue-based ideology in five multiparty systems (Argentina, Chile, Italy, Portugal, and Spain). Their results show that "affective attachments to ideological labels increase affective distance between ideological blocs to a greater extent than issue extremism and issue coherence"
