== The French Party System before 2022
The French party system has been the topic of rather significant academic attention, at least since the beginning of the Fifth Republic in 1958. However, in order to be thorough, we must split this paragraph in two: first, we will focus on pre-2015 work, focusing on the bipartisan nature of the system, and we will then go over post-2015 literature, chiefly spearheaded by Florent Gougou, which covers the collapse of French bipartism and its recomposition into a new "tripartisan" landscape. 

A comprehensive overview of late-20th century French party politics can be traced to Perraudeau @perraudeau2001systeme. Following a period of multipartism under the Fourth Republic, the birth of the Fifth and multiple concurrent factors, such as the birth of the Gaullist _UNR_ and the introduction of direct Presidential elections (a method unseen since 1848) would lead to a process of bipolarisation between the Gaullist majority and the non-Gaullist opposition. Such a process would last until 1974, which would see a further specialisation of the system into what Maurice Duverger would call a _quadrille bipolaire_: a bipartisan system with two "big" parties on each side : the PCF and PS on the left, and the UDF and RPR on the right. However, Perraudeau ends by commenting on the now-fragmented state of French politics due to a succession of changes of the party in power, unlike from 1958 to 1981, and also due to recompositions inside the left and the right themselves. 

Evans @evans2003french, in her introduction to _The French Party System_ laid out the iconoclastic character of the system. In the book, special attention is paid to the heterogeneous character of the French "left" and "right", with both encompassing multiple formations, many of which are not allied and sometimes outright opposed to each other: a good example of that is the multiplication of left-wing candidates in the 2002 presidential elections, in which four of them were from parties belonging to the incumbent government. Evans pays special attention to the Front National's attempts to present itself as "against both blocs" despite it being traditionally labeled as far-right, while observing its infortune at achieving major electoral gains due to the bipartisan and "two-block" nature of the system; still, she remarks that the "right-extremist" camp has managed to consistently grow in voter share, despite it not translating into substantial gains of seats in the legislature. Evans' takeaway, then, might be that conjectural changes have led to distortions with the traditional _quadrille_, but that those have largely taken place within a relatively stable bipartisan framework. 

Commenting on the 2007 presidential election, Grunberg @grunberg2007france seem to point towards the establishment of an UMP-PS bipartisan system, most notably thanks those parties more successfully adapting themselves to the institutional logic of the Presidential election, allowing them to gain more leverage over other parties on their side of the political landscape due to a higher vote share in those elections. This, again, would seem to confirm the "fluid-bipartisan" nature of the French political system: a small number of big, "government" parties, flanked by coalition partners who have more or less successfully carved out a niche in terms of voter base, and by extremist formations which contest the government parties from the fringes of the system. 

== The French Party System after 2022
That period of bipartism, however, seems to have come and gone. The presidential elections of 2017, have been interpreted as one of the first key markers of the recomposition of the French party system. Rafidinarivo @rafidinarivo2017dynamique studies the overseas departments, and considers the election to be a "realignment election", that is one in which the political and party system sees major and radical changes which stick in time and endures for multiple electoral occurrences afterwards. Basing herself on the surge in voter share for Marine Le Pen, the candidate of the far-right National Front, in the overseas departments, the author posits that one of the traditional bipartisan poles has been replaced overseas by Le Pen's camp, and that more generally the UMP-PS bipartism has seemingly been replaced, at least overseas, by a competition between EM! and the FN: this means the end of the _bipartisme d'alternance_. 

The French party system has seemingly moved away from a bipartisan one. But what has it become? Florent Gougou @gougou2022consolidation posits that the 2022 elections have shown that the 2017 election truly was a realignment one, with the 2022 being a "consolidation election", consolidating and cementing for the foreseeable future the new electoral order which had been creeping onto the forefront between 2017 et 2022. The French political system, Gougou says, has shifted from a bipartisan one to a "tripolar" one, in which three political and partisan poles square off against each other: a social-ecological one (represented by the NUPES and NFP coalitions),a liberal-globalist one (represented by the Ensemble coalition), and a identitarian and authoritarian conservative one (RN and allies, and R!).

Gougou, along with Guerra and Persico, have pursued such an analysis @gougou2024tripartition, in order to elaborate on the concept of "tripolarisation" and on the makeup of the three "poles": they find that each pole has a specific trend on various axes (such as, for example, authoritarianism against libertarianism or economic interventionism against laissez-faire liberalism), and that each also sees a differently-composed voter base in terms of socio-economic characteristics. Their main takeaway is that there is a key difference with previous French party systems under the Fifth Republic: while there previously could be considered to be a tripolarisation in terms of values (Left-Right-RN), the logic in terms of access to power stayed strictly bipartisan, whereas today both value system and access to power subscribe to a bipartisan logic.  

The "surprise" 2024 legislative elections would come to confirm the realignment into a tripolar party system @gougou2025france. The relative scarcity of majority governments since 2022 confirms that the tripolar makeup of the National Assembly and of the political landscape signals a clean break with the past, and shows that the French party system has become a truly tripolar one rather than a bipolar one as it used to be.


